The paper deals with algorithms for processing massive graphs in external memory, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of bisimulation, a fundamental concept in graph theory, suggests that it could also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The focus on I/O efficiency and external memory algorithms suggests that it could belong to the cs.DB (Databases) sub-category. The use of graph data and analysis of real-world datasets suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the use of locality-sensitive hashing and other techniques for reducing the computational complexity of the algorithms suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
